1 A JOINT MEMORIAL
2 REQUESTING THAT THE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPROVEMENT BOARD AND THE
3 DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT PROVIDE A REPORT ON THE
4 IMPLEMENTATION OF THE PER- AND POLY-FLUOROALKYL SUBSTANCES
5 PROTECTION ACT AND RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE CONSUMER
6 PROTECTIONS FROM PER- AND POLYFLUOROALKYL SUBSTANCES.
7
8 WHEREAS, per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances are a class
9 of thousands of synthetic chemicals added to consumer
10 products for both essential and nonessential purposes; and
11 WHEREAS, per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances may cause
12 adverse health implications, bioaccumulation in people and
13 wildlife and exhibit high persistence in the environment; and
14 WHEREAS, consumer products containing per- and
15 polyfluoroalkyl substances have been sold in New Mexico for
16 decades without required disclosures; and
17 WHEREAS, New Mexico is facing significant and increasing
18 costs to address per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances
19 contamination from the purchase, use and disposal of consumer
20 products that adversely impact public health, public drinking
21 water supplies, public wastewater systems, private drinking
22 water supplies, private septic systems, municipal solid waste
23 management and disposal infrastructure and more at the
24 expense of taxpayers; and
25 WHEREAS, during the 2025 regular legislative session, HJM 3
Page 1

1 the legislature passed House Bill 212, the Per- and Poly-
2 Fluoroalkyl Substances Protection Act, which Governor
3 Michelle Lujan Grisham signed into law on April 8, 2025; and
4 WHEREAS, the Per- and Poly-Fluoroalkyl Substances
5 Protection Act:
6 A. broadly establishes a phaseout and prohibition
7 of products with intentionally added per- and polyfluoroalkyl
8 substances and applies to the manufacturers of such products;
9 B. authorizes the environmental improvement board
10 to promulgate rules to implement the law and protect
11 consumers and the state from per- and polyfluoroalkyl
12 substances contamination;
13 C. exempts certain products containing
14 intentionally added per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances from
15 the phaseout and prohibition based on limited scientific
16 literature regarding chemical degradation, environmental
17 mobility and persistence, potential human exposure pathways
18 and possible health impacts, but does not exempt such
19 products from other aspects of the environmental improvement
20 board's authority; and
21 D. requires manufacturers of products containing
22 intentionally added per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances to
23 label such products in English and Spanish, including
24 products exempted from the phaseout and prohibition; and
25 WHEREAS, additional health and environmental studies are HJM 3
Page 2

1 needed to understand more fully the toxicological profiles,
2 exposure risks and public health implications of
3 fluoropolymers;
4 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF THE
5 STATE OF NEW MEXICO that the environmental improvement board
6 be requested to develop a report on the implementation of the
7 Per- and Poly-Fluoroalkyl Substances Protection Act,
8 including the efficacy of the rules promulgated by the
9 environmental improvement board pursuant to that act; and
10 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department of
11 environment, in consultation with other state agencies, be
12 requested to develop a report on the public health,
13 environmental and economic risks of the exemptions codified
14 in the Per- and Poly-Fluoroalkyl Substances Protection Act
15 and to provide recommendations to the legislature regarding
16 whether such exemptions, such as the exemption for
17 fluoropolymers, should be continued, modified or removed; and
18 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the department of
19 environment be requested to present preliminary findings to
20 the appropriate interim legislative committees on or before
21 December 1, 2026 and the final report to the governor and
22 legislature on or before August 1, 2027; and
23 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that copies of this memorial be
24 transmitted to the secretary of environment, the chair of the
25 environmental improvement board and the office of the HJM 3
